<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911004-0019</DOCNO><DOCID>911004-0019.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>10/04/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   FREDDIE MAC FINED at least 18 of the 25 banks and WallStreet houses that sell the U.S.-sponsored agency's debt. Thefines, for violating bidding rules, total 20% of the dealers'fees from the sale of Freddie Mac's debt for the past twoyears.   ---</LP><TEXT>   RJR Nabisco plans to sell $4.9 billion in common andpreferred stock to help the company cut debt and expand itsoverseas tobacco business. The price of RJR junk bondssurged.   ---   The Soviets could get a short-term loan from the sevenleading industrial nations to help it make bank-debtpayments, under a proposal being considered by financeministers.   ---   American Express expects to set aside in the fourthquarter up to $100 million more than previously projected forpossible loan losses. The company's stock tumbled $2.375, or9.4%, to $23 on news of troubles in the company's Optima cardbusiness.   ---   Stocks declined, as did long-term bonds and the dollar.The Dow Jones industrials fell 27.73 points to 2984.79.Treasury bond prices lost 1/8 point.   ---   Abu Dhabi's government plans to sell some of BCCI's 24branches in Britain, acknowledging little hope for a plan torestructure the global bank.   ---   Factory orders fell 1.9% in August after rising 6.1% inJuly, but economists said the recovery is on track.   ---   Sales of domestic cars and trucks surged in late Septemberto their highest rate in nearly three months, but someauto-industry executives said the good news may not last.   ---   Sun Co. and Oryx Energy plan to sell assets and cut theirstaffs amid soft demand for petroleum products. Sun expectsto take a $400 million charge against third-quarter profit.   ---   Five life insurers' debt ratings were lowered by Sandamp;P dueto concern about possible investment losses. Aetna was thebiggest of the five.   ---   Retailers said their September sales data are unlikely toshow much improvement over August's level.   ---   Union Carbide's $470 million settlement of civil claimsrelated to the 1984 Bhopal poison gas leak was up held byIndia's Supreme Court. Carbide's criminal immunity waslifted, but that move may have little effect.   ---   Oil prices gained as much as 50 cents a barrel, butRussian officials said estimates of a 50% drop this year inSoviet exports were exaggerated.   ---   House Banking Committee Democrats voted to fight for abroad bank reform bill, resisting efforts by other panels tonarrow the legislation.   ---   Tokyo stock prices climbed amid growing expectations offurther interest-rate cuts. The Nikkei average rose 336.33,or 1.4%, to 24,711.44. In London, share prices retreated. TheFT-SE 100 index lost 18.6 points.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 174,230,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2984.79, off 27.73; transportation 1198.43, off 3.36;utilities 213.19, off 0.44.   Bonds: Lehman Brothers Treasury index 4067.31, off 2.39.   Commodities: Oil $22.67 a barrel, up 34 cents. Dow Jonesfutures index 123.88, up 0.68; spot index 116.14, off 0.61.   Dollar: 130.55 yen, off 1.98; 1.6440 marks, off 0.0214.</TEXT></DOC>